ns of cultural formations. Addressing these deficiencies, Samuels uses psychoanalytic theory to examine the manifestations of racism, sexism, ethnocentrism, and homophobia in the works of Shakespeare, Mary Shelley, Joseph Conrad, and Toni Morrison, showing how these distinct modes of oppression feed off of each other and the diverse ways that cultural critics can work to undermine them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDiscrimination in literature. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aHomophobia in literature. 0aPrejudices in literature. 0aPsychoanalysis and literaturezEngland. 0aPsychoanalysis and literaturezUnited States. 0aRacism in literature. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Movements / Psychoanalysis.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079149107240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791491072423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791491072/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles